body.description: The Samsung Portable SSD T7 is the next standard in external storage. With transfer rates up to 9.5x faster than traditional external hard drives and read/ write speeds up to 1050 MB/s1, you can move massive files around with unparalleled ease and fluidity. Its sleek, shock-resistant design is uncommonly durable, capable of withstanding drops from up to 6ft3, so you can take it on-the-go with complete peace of mind. The T7 is compatible with PC, Mac, Android devices, gaming consoles, and more8. Included in the box are USB Type C-to-C and Type C-to-A cables for added convenience. All firmware and components, including Samsung's world-renowned DRAM and NAND, are produced in-house, allowing end-to-end integration for quality you can trust9. 1Performance may vary depending on host configuration. To reach maximum read/write speeds of up to 1,050/1,000 MB/s, respectively, the host device and connection cables must support USB 3.2Gen 2 and the UASP mode must be enabled. 2Based on internal test results compared to a Samsung external HDD 1TB (HX-MTD10EA). Android app available on Google Play. 8Compatibility with host devices may vary. Some operating systems may require T7 Touch reformatting. Please find the compatible devices list on Samsung.com/support. T7 Touch is compatible with USB 3.0 and USB 2.0. 9Source: 2003-Q3 2020 IHS Markit data: NAND suppliers' revenue market share. 10Included SSD cable recommended.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 10, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A Portable Powerhouse for 4K Prowess
reviews.reviewText: Dive into the realm of ultra-high-definition videography with the SAMSUNG SSD T7 Portable External Solid State Drive, boasting a colossal 2TB of space. This isn't just an external drive; it's a vault of speed and reliability, a perfect companion for your iPhone 15 Pro's 4K ProRes video shooting prowess. It's like having a personal, pocket-sized cinema archive, ready to safeguard your creative masterpieces.The SAMSUNG T7 shines brightest in its performance with 4K video files. Handling ProRes video from the iPhone 15 Pro is no small feat – it demands speed, capacity, and endurance. The T7 meets this challenge head-on, like a champion sprinter who's also a marathon runner. It's the digital workhorse that videographers dream of – fast, robust, and with space to spare.But it's not just about raw power. The portability of this SSD is a game-changer. Compact and lightweight, it's like a digital nomad's secret weapon. Whether you're capturing the urban sprawl from a rooftop or chronicling wildlife in a remote jungle, the T7 is your faithful companion, ensuring your data is always at your fingertips, safe and sound.The design and build quality also deserve a standing ovation. Encased in a sleek, durable shell, this SSD is both a style statement and a testament to resilience. It's like the James Bond of external drives – suave, sophisticated, and ready for action in the most challenging environments.TL;DR: The SAMSUNG SSD T7 Portable External Solid State Drive is a powerhouse of storage, speed, and durability, tailor-made for the demands of 4K ProRes video shooting on the iPhone 15 Pro. It's more than an external drive; it's a portable, robust vault for your high-quality video files, ensuring that your creative work is captured and preserved without a hitch. With the T7, your 4K video endeavors are in safe, capable hands.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 7, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Nice size, durable, long cord.
reviews.reviewText: This portable ssd drive is a nice size; not too small not too large. the cord is a plus for this item; nice an long; not one of those short ones just a few inches long. This cord is 18 inches; YES! Finally not a micro length cord. the copy write speed is very good; speedy downloads and backup copy of files and documents. Easy to take on the go. The product is very well built. I use one for my Linux box pc also; no problems with partitioning so far. I should be able to dual boot into this portable ssd with my LinuxMint OS. So far so good; no problems. time will tell if this ssd drive will last or not. Some of the other portable ssd drives did not last very long.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on August 20, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Solid, reliable, familiar...
reviews.reviewText: I now own several generations (and 3 colors!) of Samsung T SSDs- T3, T5, T7 plus the Shield version.They've been my long-time go-to, especially as prices come down and file sizes go up.Thin-sliced from my 1st review: It's an easy-to-use and very secure little device, fast and simple to use across devices and even systems, as plugging in it opens a choice of OS and a window to log-in. The password is always what you assign at set-up, and it's hard-wired into the device, so it stays secure, requiring password every time it's first connected.Tech specs you can read. It's fast, blazing when connected to other SSD's. Gets a little toasty with huge transfers (like my 1GB initial transfer from another drive). It comes with two types of USB cables, which work well, and secure it well even if pulled around a bit on its short length. I'd note that the T7 Shield is an exception, consistently coming (in my experience) with a poorly designed connector/receptacle, nearly impossible to keep a solid connection unless you don't breathe or vibrate things when you type. That bad.I digress. This - the basic T7 (newer software interface but basically same as T5 - is one of those things that "just works". Like the others, on the Mac it may hava some small quirks - like saying it's disconnected when you first connect, or similar, but it works fine, 100% of the time for me thus far, all of them (knock on wood). Unless you really truly like the idea of the ridged design and heat-dissipation of the Shield, I'd advise against it (I called Samsung, they said they'd send a new cord, and didn't, and claim not to know about the port/plug issue). That off my chest, I love and swear by the T5s and T7s, and caveat emptor on the Shields.
